				\begin{document}$$\begin{array}{l}{\rm{Correlation}}\,{\rm{in}}\,{\rm{control}}\,{\rm{condition}}:\frac{1}{{{\rm{m}}}_{{\rm{x}}}-1}\sum _{{\rm{k}}=1}^{{{\rm{m}}}_{{\rm{x}}}}(\frac{{x}_{{\rm{ik}}}-{\mu }_{{\rm{xi}}}}{{\sigma }_{{\rm{xi}}}}\cdot \frac{{x}_{{\rm{jk}}}-{\mu }_{{\rm{xj}}}}{{\sigma }_{{\rm{xj}}}})\\ {\rm{Correlation}}\,{\rm{in}}\,{\rm{case}}\,{\rm{condition}}:\frac{1}{{{\rm{m}}}_{{\rm{y}}}-1}\sum _{{\rm{k}}=1}^{{{\rm{m}}}_{{\rm{y}}}}(\frac{{y}_{{\rm{ik}}}-{\mu }_{{\rm{yi}}}}{{\sigma }_{{\rm{yi}}}}\cdot \frac{{{\rm{y}}}_{{\rm{jk}}}-{\mu }_{{\rm{yj}}}}{{\sigma }_{{\rm{yj}}}})\end{array}$$\end{document}Correlationincontrolcondition:1mx−1∑k=1mx(xik−μxiσxi⋅xjk−μxjσxj)Correlationincasecondition:1my−1∑k=1my(yik−μyiσyi⋅yjk−μyjσyj)where, there are mx control samples and my case samples; for a control sample k, its expressions on genes i and j are xik and xjk; the expression average and variance for gene i (or gene j) on control samples are μxi and σxi (or μxj and σxj); and conveniently, the sample in case has these similar variables and annotations but with index y. Note that a gene can be replaced by a molecule in this mathematical framework.
